1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3 g6 $5 {The only system where we choose to
fianchetto our dark-squared bishop. It turns out that a3 move is pretty
useless against g6 and therefore Black is able to equalize easily.} 5. g3 ({
Another White set-up is} 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {White has also tried unusual} (6.
Qc2 O-O 7. Be2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. h4 {,but it wasn't successfull} h6 10. Bc4
Nce7 $1 11. Ba2 c6 12. d3 b6 13. e4 Nc7 14. Be3 Be6 $15 {and Black was
definitely better in Iturrizaga Bonelli, E (2658)-Rabiega, R (2498) Germany 2017
in some sort of a reversed Najdorf Sicilian position.}) 6... O-O 7. O-O d5 8.
cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qc2 {now I would recommend the following idea} Re8 10. d3 Nxc3 $1
11. bxc3 Na5 {with idea to follow up with c7-c5.} 12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 {
White would be doing great if not} c5 $1 {An idea borrowed from the Gruenfeld
defence!} 14. Rd1 Bf5 15. Qa2 Be6 16. d5 {this occurred in Drozdowski-Sevian,
Dallas 2015 Black could have played} Bd7 $146 17. Bb2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Ba4 19. Rd3
c4 20. Rd4 Rc8 {with serious initiative on the queenside.}) 5... Bg7 6. Bg2
O-O 7. O-O d5 $1 {Due to a3-move, which is somewhat a waste of time Black has
time to strike in the center} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxe5 {Critical reaction,
certainly White has other more positional alternatives} (9. d3 Nde7 {since
Black is unable to play 9...о Pe6 in view of 10. о ..g5 the text seems the
most reliable. A good model game here is} 10. Bd2 a5 11. Rb1 h6 12. b4 axb4 13.
axb4 Nd4 {This knight jump is thematic in such positions. Black gains space.}
14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Ne4 {Kortschnoj-Gelfand, Odessa 2008} Ra2 $146 16. b5 b6 $15
{would secure a slightly better position for Black. His space advantage should
not be underestimated.}) (9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. d3 Qb5 {Sooner or later Black has
to move his queen away from d5 and this looks like an appropriate moment for
doing so.} 11. Rb1 {another line here} (11. Qc2 a5 12. a4 (12. Be3 {occured in
Van Tienhoven-Kitson, ICCF email 2006 I found an interesting idea here} e4 $5
13. dxe4 a4 $44 {with rich compensation. With e5-e4, Black has simultaneously
succeeded to open up his dark-squared and lock down opponent's light-squared
bishop.}) 12... Qb6 13. Be3 Nd4 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bf4 c6 16. Rfb1 Re8 17. b4
axb4 18. Bd6 Bg4 19. Bf1 Qd8 20. Bxb4 Qd7 $11 {and very logical play ended in
a balanced position Roos-Vareille, Chambery 1994}) 11... a5 12. Be3 {Gurevich,
M (2633)-Balogh,C (2561) Kusadasi 2006 I prefer an immediate} Nd4 $5 $146 {
it's hard to see how White can pose Black any problems, for example} 13. b4
axb4 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Bd2 c6 16. Bxb4 Re8 {with equal game}) 9... Nxc3 10.
Nxc6 Nxe2+ $1 11. Qxe2 bxc6 12. Bxc6 Rb8 13. d3 Be6 {and White cannot untangle
his queenside without playing} 14. Rb1 {so his extra pawn is irrelevant.} ({
White also tried} 14. Re1 {but after} Bd4 {anyway played} 15. Rb1 Ba2 16. Ra1 {
and draw was agreed in McNab-Geenen, England 1999}) 14... Ba2 15. Ra1 Be6 $11 {
with a move repetition.} *

