1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d3 {Definitely not a very challenging line,
but White just wants to play the Sicilian with a tempo up.} d5 {Obviously Black
has other options, but the text fits perfectly to our repertoire} 5. cxd5 Nxd5
6. e3 ({In case of} 6. g3 Bc5 {should transpose to our main lines after} 7. Bg2
O-O 8. O-O Bb6) 6... Be7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 {Finally we arrived at the
well-known Scheveningen position with colors reversed and therefore with an
extra tempo for White. There have been a bunch of games played here, but I will
try to cover just the main directions in order to help Black player understand
the main ideas.} 9. a3 ({Other options are:} 9. Bd2 Nb6 $1 {This is a thematic
reaction to White's previous move since White was planning to play Nxd4
followed up by Bc3.} 10. a3 a5 11. Na4 (11. b3 f5 12. Qc2 {will be covered
via 11.Nd2}) 11... Nxa4 12. Qxa4 Qd7 13. Kh1 {Black was threatening 13...Nd4} f6 14. Rac1 Rfd8 15. Rg1 Bd6 16. g4 {Probably a risky plan.} g5 $1 17. Bc3
Bd5 $15 {Black chance s are preferable Lendwai,R (2397)-Caruana,F (2712)
Rogaska Slatina 2011, although position is complex and requires precise
maneuvering.}) (9. Qc2 f5 10. a3 {just transposes to our main line.}) 9... a5
10. Qc2 f5 {A very important crossroad for White, who can choose different
plans:} 11. Na4 (11. Re1 Kh8 12. Bd2 Nb6 13. b3 Bf6 14. Rab1 {this occurred in
Bosboom,M (2385) -Ermenkov,E (2475) Amsterdam 1988 I believe Black should play
aggressive} g5 $146 15. Bc1 g4 16. Nd2 Qd7 {with thematic Scheveningen play,
where I feel Black is doing fine.}) (11. Bd2 Nb6 {thematic reaction after Bd2.} 12. b3 Bf6 13. Rab1 ({White was very successful after} 13. Rfc1 Qe7 14.
Be1 {Bischoff, K (2553) -Tiviakov, S (2637) Germany 2011, but I believe Black's
play can be improved upon:} g5 $146 {This is Black's most ambitious idea in
such positions.} 15. Nd2 g4 16. Nc4 h5 {with complex, but promising position
for Black.}) 13... Qe7 14. Bc1 g5 15. Na4 g4 16. Nd2 Nd7 {Not letting white
take control over c5-square. Black was doing fine in Garcia Gonzales-Timman,
Buenos Aires 1978}) (11. Rd1 Kh8 12. Rb1 Qe8 {is another thematic Scheveningen
idea, which works well here} 13. Bd2 Qg6 14. Be1 Rad8 $15 {Black chances look
preferable in Kramnik-Adams, Las Vegas 1999.}) 11... Qd6 12. Rd1 Rad8 {and
Black has nothing to complain about Van Wely, L (2692)-Karjakin, S (2769) Wijk
aan Zee 2012. Karjakin's plan in the game was to swing the queen over to the
kingside via the 6-th rank after retreating with the bishop.} *

