1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e4 {A very tricky move, after which White
set-up resembles Botvinnik variation with c4 and e4 pawns.} Bc5 {The most
challenging} 5. Nxe5 {It goes without saying, that this is the critical line.
White can hardly afford to play a positional game after he neglected d4-square.
Just one model game} (5. Be2 d6 6. d3 h6 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 Nh7 {a thematic idea
in this kind of structure. It opens up the f-pawn and sometimes aims to move
the knight to g5, increasing control over d4 square.} 9. Be3 Nd4 $1 10. Bxd4
Bxd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nb5 c5 13. Bg4 a6 14. Na3 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Rxf5
17. f4 Qf6 18. Qf3 Rf8 $40 {and Black was better in Mejzlik-Luch, Litomysl 2005
}) 5... Nxe5 6. d4 Bb4 $1 7. dxe5 Nxe4 {And now we have a major crossroad in
this line.} 8. Qd4 {other options:} (8. Qd3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5 $1 10. Ba3 ({
White also tried} 10. Qg3 O-O 11. Bh6 {which obviously runs into} Bxc3+ $1 12.
Qxc3 (12. Kd1 Bxe5) 12... gxh6 {after} 13. f4 d6 14. O-O-O {White could claim
some compensation in Grigoryan-Rublevsky, Ruma 2017, still Black is pretty
safe after the best} Be6 $146 15. Bd3 Qh4 16. g3 Qg4 17. Rhe1 (17. h3 Qg7)
17... Rad8 $15) 10... Qg5 11. Qd4 (11. g3 d6 $1 {we have one game here} 12. f4
Qg6 {and Black has nothing to worry about after the queen exchange.} 13. O-O-O
Qxd3 14. Rxd3 ({not much better for White is} 14. Bxd3 dxe5 15. Kc2 Bd7 $15 {
with better endgame}) 14... Bf5 15. Re3 Bb6 16. Re1 O-O-O $15 {and Black was
definitely slightly better in Poldauf,D (2385)-Schlosser,P (2591)/Berlin 2012})
11... d6 12. exd6 O-O $1 {Black's lead in development is starting to look
quite dangerous.} 13. Be2 Re8 14. Kf1 cxd6 15. Bxd6 Qg6 $44 {and Black has
more than sufficient compensation due to White king on f1, as in Onischuk,
A-Baklan, Germany 1998, GER-chT}) (8. Qf3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5 10. Be2 ({There are
no problems for Black also after} 10. Ba3 d6 $1 11. exd6 O-O {Black was fine
in Rohde-Dlugy, New York op 1990}) (10. Qg3 {see this position via 8. о Bg3})
10... d6 11. Qg3 ({White has little compensation after} 11. O-O dxe5 12. Ba3
Qf6 13. Qe3 c6 14. Bf3 Bb6 15. Qe2 {Ju,W (2557)-Kosteniuk,A (2529) Chengdu
2015 and now} Qe6 $146 16. Rfd1 Bc7 17. Rd2 f5 18. Rad1 Kf7 19. Bd6 Bxd6 20.
Rxd6 Qe7 $15 {and Black consolidates his position with pawn up.}) 11... O-O 12.
Bh6 Bxc3+ {we already familiar with this tactical pattern} 13. Qxc3 gxh6 14.
exd6 Qxd6 15. Rd1 Qe7 16. Rd3 Bf5 17. Re3 Qh4 {White has compensation for
being a pawn down but hardly more than that Benes-Berko, ICCF email 2010}) (8.
Qc2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bc5 10. Bd3 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. O-O Be6 {This is a nice
thing in this variation - Black can castle on either side of the board,
depending on the circumstances.} 13. Rb1 {or} (13. Bf5 O-O-O 14. Bg5 Rde8 15.
Rad1 Qa6 16. Bxe6+ Qxe6 {and White problematic pawn structure should tell in
long-term, as in Fedukin-Anikeev, ICCF email 2012}) 13... O-O-O 14. Be4 Bb6 15.
Qe2 Kb8 16. Be3 Bc8 $15 {and Black was slightly better in Fedukin-Baranov,
ICCF email 2013}) (8. Qg4 $2 {does not work due to} Nxc3 9. Bd2 ({If} 9. a3 {
then} Bf8 10. bxc3 d6 11. Qg3 Qe7 12. f4 g6 13. Bd3 Bg7 14. Ra2 O-O 15. O-O
dxe5 $17 {and Black large positional advantage is beyond any doubts
Medak-Rubil, Bol na Bracu 2014}) 9... O-O 10. bxc3 Qe7 11. Qe4 Bd6 $1 $146 {
a nice finesse instead of} (11... Bc5 12. Bd3 {which has been played in both
games.}) 12. f4 Bc5 13. Bd3 f5 14. Qe2 d6 $17 {and Black is clearly better as
he challenges white's strong e5 pawn, after which all white will be left are
weak pawns on the queenside.}) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 {It is important to keep in
mind that this is a risky strategic course for White since he has allowed a
significant damage to his queenside pawn structure. He is hoping to use his
space advantage to create a dangerous initiative. However, as we will see,
Black has enough resources to fend off White's attempts and try to use his
positional advantage in later stages of the game.} Be7 {Another crossroad for
White} 10. Qg4 (10. Bd3 d6 11. Bf4 {is another direction} (11. exd6 Qxd6 12.
O-O {is a pretty tame line.} Be6 13. Bf4 (13. Qxg7 O-O-O {dangerous for White.}
) 13... Qxd4 14. cxd4 {this occured in Debray,T (2109)-Doornbos,Y (2321)
Drancy 2005 the most precise here would have been} Rd8 $1 $146 15. d5 c6 16.
dxc6 bxc6 17. Rfd1 O-O $11 {with equal endgame.}) 11... dxe5 12. Bxe5 (12.
Qxd8+ Bxd8 13. Bxe5 {not dangerous either} f6 14. Bf4 {Reveillere-Navrotescu,
Rochefort 2004 Black should have played} Be6 $146 15. O-O Kf7 16. Be4 Rb8 17.
Rfd1 Be7 {with equality.}) 12... O-O 13. O-O (13. Bxg7 {loses to} c5 $1 14.
Qxd8 Rxd8) 13... Re8 $1 {another important tactical nuance.} 14. Rfe1 {white
cannot play} (14. Bxg7 $2 {in view of} c5 {losing a piece.}) 14... Qxd4 15.
cxd4 {Reede-Turner, LSS email 2011 the arising endgame is pretty harmless.
Black should just play} c6 $146 16. Rab1 b6 17. Be4 Bd7 $11 {with equality.}) (
10. Bf4 O-O 11. Bd3 d6 12. O-O {occured in Zhao-Krush, Khanty-Mansiysk 2014 I
would recommend here} Re8 $146 13. Rad1 g6 14. Rfe1 Be6 {and Black has no
problems whatsoever as he has completed development. It would do him good to
trade at least a pair of pieces to gain more operating space.}) 10... Kf8 {
I prefer this move to 10...g6.} 11. Qe4 {Other possibilities:} (11. Qg3 d6 12.
Be3 (12. Bf4 Bh4 $1 {A strong idea, forcing favorable piece trades that
undermine White's e5 pawn.} 13. Qe3 g5 14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. hxg3 dxe5 16. Qxe5 {
Cehic-Jukic, Bled 1999 and Black, of course, should have played} Qe7 17. Qxe7+
Kxe7 $15 {with better endgame.}) 12... Bh4 $1 {again this idea works extremely
well here} 13. Qf4 dxe5 14. Qxe5 Bf6 15. Qc5+ Kg8 $15 {and Black was
positionally better Heinzl, O-Kristol, L corr 1988}) (11. Be3 d6 12. Qe4 {
transposition to 11. Qe4}) (11. Be2 d6 12. Qe4 dxe5 13. Qxe5 (13. O-O Bd6 {
and it looks like White doesn't have too many resources, although he does have
some initiative.} 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. Be3 f5 16. Qd5 Qf7 17. Qb5 a6 18. Qb2 {
Shinkevich-Babikov, Moscow 2009 Black could have played} Be7 $1 $146 19. Bc5
Kg8 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Rd5 e4 {and Black's extra pawn should tell.}) 13... Bd6
14. Qd4 Qe7 15. O-O $2 {this idea just fails. Meanwhile, the best} (15. Be3 {
was White's best option. After} Bf5 16. c5 Be5 {Black is fine.}) 15... Qxe2 16.
Ba3 Be6 $19 {and White lost Humeau-Fomichenko, Pic d'Anie 2006}) (11. Qf3 d6
12. exd6 {Another line here} (12. Bf4 h5 13. Bd3 g5 $1 {Black clearly takes
over. He needs not to worry about his king as it is quite safe on f8. On the
other hand, white pieces will be running out of good squares soon.} 14. exd6
Bf6 15. Bd2 Qxd6 16. O-O Bg4 17. c5 {Ljubojevic-Kramnik, Monte Carlo 2002
Black best chance would have been} Qxh2+ $146 18. Kxh2 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Rd8 20.
Bxg5 Bxg5 21. Be4 b6 {and White still has to work in order to achieve draw.})
12... Qxd6 13. Bf4 {Hickl-Braun,M Germany 1986 after precise} Qf6 $1 $146 14.
Bxc7 Qxf3 15. gxf3 Be6 $15 {White is bound to suffer in this endgame with a
terrible pawn structure on both flanks.}) 11... d6 12. Be3 {Other options are
clearly worse} (12. Bf4 dxe5 13. Bxe5 Bf6 14. f4 g6 {Completing artificial
castling.} 15. Be2 Kg7 16. O-O Qe7 $15 {Black has solved the problem of his
king and his positional advantage is obvious Eljanov-Rublevsky, Sochi 2006}) (
12. f4 dxe5 13. fxe5 Bd7 $1 {This idea is important as it allows black to
fully mobilize his queenside pieces.} 14. h4 ({On} 14. Qxb7 {very strong is}
Qe8 $1 {followed by Bc6, when white's lag in development becomes a serious
issue.}) 14... Bc6 15. Qf4 Qd7 16. Rh3 Re8 {and Black took over in
Bukal-Gabrielsen, Oslo 2004}) 12... dxe5 13. Rd1 Qe8 14. Qxe5 {after a pretty
forced sequence of moves Black has some choice. I prefer straightforward} Bd6
15. Qxe8+ ({Another direction is} 15. Qh5 Be5 16. Be2 Bxc3+ 17. Kf1 Be6 18. Qf3
{McNab-Gormally, Newcastle on Tyne 1998 simple} b6 $1 $146 {would maintain
better position for Black.} 19. Bxb6 axb6 20. Qxc3 Rxa2 {is definitely to
Black's advantage.}) 15... Kxe8 16. Bd4 Kf8 17. c5 Be7 18. Be5 $2 {an
unfortunate move.} ({White should have played} 18. Bc4 h5 19. O-O Rh6 {with a
pretty equal game.}) 18... Be6 19. Bxc7 Bxc5 $15 {Black was already better in
Oussedik-Traore, Nouakchott 2013. White's pawn structure is not flattering at
all.} *

