1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4 {A relatively rare guest on GM-level,
however quite a tricky line.} exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 {Top Black's choice and, in my
opinion, the best reaction.} 6. Bg5 {Main move. I also considered two major
alternatives for White:} (6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Bxc3+ {Most probably Black has
other reliable options at his disposal, but the text seems to be the most
aggressive.} 8. bxc3 Ne5 9. c5 ({Significantly worse is} 9. Qb3 d6 10. O-O Nfd7
$1 {and Black is much better positionally as has been convincingly proven in
the following game} 11. a4 Nc5 12. Qa2 a5 {Black knights have assumed
wonderful outposts and c4 pawn is chronically weak.} 13. Nb3 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 Rb8
15. Bf4 Nd7 16. Qb5 b6 $17 {Kryvoruchko,Y (2612)-Karjakin,S (2732)/Alushta 2008
}) 9... Qe7 10. Nb3 ({Other options:} 10. Nb5 {sacrificing the pawn for
initiative.} Qxc5 11. Rb1 Nc4 12. Qd4 (12. Bf4 {this occurred in Heberla,B 
(2539)-Ram, S (2338) Mumbai 2011 Black should have played naturally} d6 $146 {
and after a pretty forced sequence of moves} 13. Qd4 Bf5 14. Rb4 Be6 15. Qxc5
dxc5 16. Rb1 Bf5 17. Rc1 c6 18. Nd6 Nxd6 19. Bxd6 Rfe8 20. Bxc5 Re5 $1 {
Black has better endgame as white has not completed his development yet and
has a couple of weak pawns.}) 12... Qxd4 13. cxd4 Ne8 $1 $15 {Buchaillot,L 
(1889)-Khan, V (2105) LSS email 2012 and White has to work hard to prove he has
enough for the pawn.}) (10. Rb1 Qxc5 11. Nb5 {is just a transposition to 10. о
..b5}) 10... Rb8 $1 {Very human decision: Black needs b7-b6 move in order to
untangle his queenside.} 11. O-O b6 {White has tried other moves as well:} 12.
cxb6 (12. f4 {Bernal Moro,L (2212)-Anderskewitz,R (2266) LSS email 2010 here I
like natural} Nc6 $146 {instead of allowing complications after 12...о ..c4.
White has to play} 13. e4 {a logical sequence of moves here would be} Nxe4 14.
Re1 f5 15. Ba3 Bb7 16. Nd2 Na5 $1 {and Black is perfectly fine.}) (12. Re1 $2 {
is hardly a good idea} bxc5 13. f4 Nc4 {This is the ideal square for a black
knight in such Nimzo-Indian positions.} 14. e4 d6 15. Qe2 Ba6 $1 16. Na5 Qe6
$17 {and Black was clearly better in Seirawan-Van Wely, Elista RUS 1998}) 12...
axb6 13. Re1 Re8 {Black has solved his opening problems and can hope to take
over in long-term due to his better pawn structure. We have one game here,
which continued} 14. a4 Bb7 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. e4 Ra7 17. f4 Nc4 18. Qd3 d5 19.
e5 Qd8 20. Nd4 Ra8 $1 {with a double-edged game Voetter,H (2121)-Papenfuss,I 
(2249) GER email 2012}) ({It is hard to imagine that} 6. Nxc6 bxc6 {can pose
Black any problems. One of the recent examples here is} 7. Bd2 O-O 8. e3 d5 9.
a3 Be7 10. Be2 Be6 11. O-O dxc4 12. Qc2 {Danchevski,O (2367)-Nepomniachtchi,I 
(2733) Antalya 2017 and now I suggest} Rb8 $146 {with a slightly better game
for Black since white yet has to return the lost pawn, while black has several
active ideas such as Rb3-Qb8 or Ng4-e5-d3, etc.}) 6... d5 $5 {A rare move,
which I analyzed some twenty years ago after my friend Alex Finkel employed it
in his game. It appears to still be very interesting and fully reliable
alternative to more popular 6...h6, 6...0-0 and 6...Bxc3} 7. e3 ({The
the above-mentioned game saw} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qa4 ({Critical seems to me} 8. cxd5 {
as occurred in Loucek-Soukup, Czechia 2007 Black should respond with} Qxd5 $146
9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. e3 Rb8 $1 {and I believe his bishop pair should be sufficient
compensation for the damaged pawn structure.}) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qd6 $1 {
draw agreed in Ye Rongguang-Finkel, A/Dutch Open, Dieren NED 1997 the arising
position is quite unclear} 10. cxd5 {, or} (10. e3 Ne4 11. Bf4 Qf6) 10... Nxd5
11. Rd1 f6 12. Bc1 Qc5 $13) 7... O-O 8. Nxc6 ({The natural alternative} 8. cxd5
Qxd5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 {has not been played in practice. Black seems to be very
active, for example} 10. Qd2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Rd8 $1 $15 {with better game.}) 8...
bxc6 9. Be2 ({I found a remarkable game between two computers here} 9. Qb3 Rb8
10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 d4 $1 12. exd4 Re8+ 13. Be2 h6 14. Be3 Ne4 15. Qc1 Rb3
16. O-O Nxf2 $1 17. Rxf2 Rbxe3 18. Qd2 c5 $11 {and Black was not worse Bouquet
1.6-Critter 1.6a CCRL 2013}) (9. a3 {is definitely not challenging as it loses
an important tempo in the opening.} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qd6 $1 {This is always a
convenient way to unpin the knight. Ne4 is a threat now.} 11. Qd4 c5 12. Qf4
Ne4 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. Bh4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Be6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 {and the arising
endgame is clearly favourable for Black Critter 1.6-Bouquet 1.6 CCRL 2013})
9... h6 10. Bh4 {and now Black can seize the initiative in the style of
Ragozin defence with} g5 $1 11. Bg3 Ne4 $5 12. Rc1 {this occurred in the game
Solonar,S (2355)-Zude,A (2406) Erlensee 2007} (12. Qc2 Bf5 13. Bd3 {only move.}
d4 $5 {a very aggressive and interesting approach.} ({Meanwhile} 13... Bxc3+
14. bxc3 Re8 $15 {is safe and slightly better for Black.}) 14. Bxe4 dxc3 15.
O-O Bxe4 16. Qxe4 cxb2 17. Rad1 {Spreng,S (2320)-Fette,M (2290) Krumbach 1985
when simple} Qe7 $1 $146 {would keep clear edge, since White cannot win
b2-pawn.}) {Black certainly should have chosen} 12... Bf5 $1 $146 {with the
idea} 13. O-O Nxc3 14. bxc3 Ba3 $1 $17 {winning the exchange.} *

