1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Nd5 ({I would like to mention also
} 5. d4 exd4 {It goes without saying Black has other reliable options as well.}
6. exd4 (6. Nxd4 {doesn't look serious, although I found quite a few games
here. I would recommend the following course of action for Black:} O-O 7. Be2
Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bc5 10. O-O b6 11. Rd1 Bb7 {and Black seems to me
already slightly better due to White's problematic pawn structure, as in
Skatchkov-Turov, Minsk 2000}) 6... O-O 7. Bd3 d5 8. O-O Bg4 9. Be3 dxc4 10.
Bxc4 Qd6 $1 {Black's position is very comfortable and resembles a harmless
