1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8.
d3 Bb6 9. Nxd5 {This is another direction for White.} Qxd5 10. b4 $5 {This
move is the most serious try for White and the one which brought Daniil Dubov
a remarkable victory over Sergey Karjakin at the World Cup in Tbilisi 2017.} ({
I don't think White has other moves to challenge Black's position. Just one
example here:} 10. Qa4 {Passos Coutinho, E (1764)-Deste, D (1915) Cuiaba 2015 I
think Black should have played} Qd6 11. b3 Rd8 {with very comfortable play in
the view of easy development and full central control (for example white can
only dream about the thematic central break d3-d4).}) 10... a5 $5 {This looks
like a very interesting novelty in this line.} ({Sergey Karjakin twice opted
for} 10... e4 11. Ng5 Qd4 12. Ba3 $1 {is the most challenging move.} ({Sergey
also faced} 12. Be3 Qxb4 13. Nxe4 Bxe3 $1 {This is an improvement.} ({The
first game between the same opponents saw} 13... Bg4 {where White could have
hoped for an advantage after} 14. h3 Bh5 15. Rb1 Qe7 16. Qd2 (16. Qc2 $5 {
could be an improvement for White, intending to continue with 17.Bc5.}) 16...
Rad8 {Nakamura,H (2792)-Karjakin,S (2773) Saint Louis 2017 and now} 17. Rfc1
$14 {would maintain a slight edge for White due to the pressure along the
semi-open files on the queenside.}) 14. fxe3 Qe7 15. Qd2 Ne5 16. Rac1 ({
Most probably White should have choosen} 16. d4 {in which case the play might
have continued with} Ng4 17. h3 Nh6 18. Rf4 c6 19. Raf1 f6 $13 {with an
unclear game. The pawn structure is unbalanced and both sides have their pros
and cons. Black is definitely solid enough.}) 16... c6 17. Nc5 Ng4 $1 18. e4 b6
19. Na4 {Nakamura, H (2792)-Karjakin, S (2773) Saint Louis 2017 and now Black
should have just played} Rd8 $146 20. Nb2 c5 $15 {with a clear positional
advantage for Black due to the rock-solid dark-square blockade (after Ng4-e5
maneuver).}) 12... e3 {Now we have a pretty forced sequence of moves} 13. b5
exf2+ 14. Kh1 Ne5 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. a4 a5 $1 17. bxa6 Rxa6 18. a5 {this all
occurred in Dubov, D (2666) -Karjakin, S (2773) Tbilisi GEO 2017 and, according
to Karjakin, he forgot his drawish line and I assume he meant this:} Rxa5 $146
19. Rxa5 Bxa5 20. Nxh7+ Ke7 21. Ng5 (21. Qc1 f6 {is also fine for black.})
21... Bb6 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation, but probably Sergey's lines
go much further.}) ({Too slow seems to me} 10... Re8 11. Bb2 Qd6 12. b5 Nd4 13.
a4 a6 14. a5 Bc5 15. bxa6 Rxa6 16. Nd2 $14 {White got a pleasant edge in
Gelfand, B (2729)-Inarkiev, E (2702) Nazran 2017}) 11. bxa5 {This is definitely
not the way to fight for an advantage and I anticipate White will try other
moves. I checked some of them:} (11. Bb2 e4 $1 (11... axb4 12. Nxe5 $14 {
is better for White after he captures on c6 as well and doubles black's pawns.}
) 12. Nd2 Qh5 $1 {Another accurate move} (12... axb4 13. Nc4 {is less clear.})
13. Bxe4 {Other moves are not impressive at all} (13. Nxe4 Bg4 $1 {is very
annoying for White.}) (13. bxa5 exd3 14. exd3 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Nxa5 $11 {leads
to an endgame where only black can be pushing against white's isolated pawns.})
13... axb4 14. a3 Bg4 15. Bf3 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 bxa3 17. Bxa3 Nd4 $1 (17... Rfe8 {
is also fine for Black.}) 18. Bxf8 Rxa1 19. Qxa1 Nxe2+ 20. Kg2 Nf4+ $1 21. gxf4
Qg4+ $11 {with perpetual.}) (11. Ng5 Qd8 12. b5 Nd4 13. a4 Bg4 14. Re1 h6 {
and Black has no problems whatsoever.}) 11... Nxa5 12. Qc2 $6 {This looks like
a blunder to me.} ({Better would have been} 12. Bb2 f6 13. Nd2 (13. Nxe5 {
is not working due to} Qb5 $1 {and White loses material.}) 13... Qf7 {and this
looks like a playable position. Once again, we can see how the black bishop is
placed actively on the g1-a7 diagonal, preventing any central activity from
white. and this looks like a playable position. Max Illingworth suggested} 14.
Bc3 Rd8 15. a4 {with slight pull, however I believe after} Bd4 $1 16. Bxd4 {or}
(16. Qc2 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Ra7) 16... exd4 17. Qc2 Ra7 {followed up by 18...b6
Black should be able to equalize easily.}) 12... Nb3 $1 {Probably Boris missed
this move} 13. Rb1 Nxc1 14. Rfxc1 Rxa2 15. Rb2 Rxb2 (15... Ra6 {is also good.})
16. Qxb2 Re8 $15 {and White has hardly enough for being pawn down Gelfand,B 
(2729)-Wang,H (2702) Tbilisi 2017} *

