1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8.
d3 Bb6 9. Bd2 {Just the most natural approach for White in the spirit of the
Sicilian. White's intention is to follow-up with о Rc1 and then depending on
the situation to play о ..xd5 , or о ..a4(e4).} Bg4 10. Rc1 (10. Na4 Qd6 ({
The natural} 10... Qd7 $5 11. Rc1 Rad8 {also looks perfectly fine for Black.
Important point , that} 12. Nc5 {runs into powerful} Bxc5 13. Rxc5 e4 $1 {
and Black takes over.}) 11. Rc1 Rad8 12. Nxb6 {This capture was also possible
in the Eljanov-Grischuk game from Chapter 1. In both cases, it solidifies
black's queenside pawn structure.} axb6 13. Re1 {this is the position from the
game Tari,A (2591)-Goh,W (2446) Barcelona 2017. After the natural} f5 $146 14.
Qb3 f4 {Black's position is very promising with the looming kingside attack.})
({It's important to mention thematic tactical idea} 10. Nxe5 {[%mdl 32768]
mentioned by Max Illingworth. it fails to impress after} Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Nxe5 12.
Bxe5 Re8 13. d4 (13. h3 Bh5 {doesn't change anything.}) 13... Bxe2 $1 14. Qxe2
Bxd4 15. Bxb7 Rxe5 16. Qf3 Rb8 {and it's definitely White, who has to be very
careful here.}) 10... Re8 $5 $146 {when the play could develop as follows:} (
10... Nxc3 {This move was played by Caruana I am not sure about this decision
and therefore I would like to propose two interesting alternatives:} 11. Bxc3
Re8 ({After} 11... Qd7 12. b4 (12. Nd2 Bh3) 12... a6 13. a4 {I like White
position since he starts the typical minority attack that puts pressure on
Black's queenside.}) 12. b4 Qd6 {I failed to find how Black can equalize here:}
(12... Qe7 13. a4 a6 14. a5 Ba7 15. e3 $14 {The bishop has become ineffective
on a7.}) (12... a5 13. b5 Nd4 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. a4 Qe7 16. h3 {and}) (12... Qd7
13. a4 a6 14. Nd2 $14 {in all cases White play looks more convenient. As we
saw earlier, the minority attack puts pressure on the queenside, while the
knight maneuver to c4 adds to the pressure. In such positions it is not always
easy to do find the best moves for the defending side.}) 13. Nd2 Qh6 14. Nc4 Qh5 {
this position occurred in Anand, V (2783)-Caruana, F (2807) Saint Louis 2017 for
some reason Vishy chose 15. о Rc2, while the most natural} 15. Re1 $146 {
would be much stronger, for example} Nd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qc2 c6 18. e3 Bb6
19. b5 $1 $16) ({The useful} 10... h6 $5 $146 {is also worthy of consideration.
The play might develop in different ways, but I would like to mention only
that Black is ready for} 11. Nxe5 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 ({Certainly White cannot play} 
12. Nxc6 Nxd1 13. Nxd8 Nxf2 $1) 12... Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Re8 $1 14. h3 Bh5 15. d4
Bxe2 $1 16. Qxe2 Bxd4 $11 {and the position simplifies into an equal game.})
11. h3 (11. Na4 Nd4 ({Worth considering is} 11... Qd7 12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. Rxc5 Nb6
{with normal play for Black. He would like to continue with f6 and, if
possible, Nd4 and c6, when he would have absolutely no weaknesses.}) 12. e3 ({
Or} 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Re1 c6 {The pressure on e2 makes black's chances not
worse. He just needs to make sure that he gives enough support to his d4 pawn
after the exchange on b6 (or Nc5).}) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 c6 {
in both cases, Black has an adequate play. Quite a few pieces have already been exchanged, without white creating anything concrete.}) 11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 ({
In case of the other recapture} 12. bxc3 {Black should continue} Bf5 13. Ng5
Qe7 {with a complicated game.}) 12... Bf5 13. Nd2 Qd7 14. Kh2 Rad8 {Black's
position looks very reliable as he is fully centralized.} *

